{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-00347/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-00347"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:03:47"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["medium shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["eye-level"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["mobile, pan, tracking"]}},{"label":{"none":["Lighting"]},"value":{"none":["high key"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["single shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A woman dons a white lab coat."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-00347","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-00347"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/canvas/1/add2c51d-c8f4-4b24-89bc-3bfbc307e600","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T14:59:29.627Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>In an <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW240663235 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.bbc.com/culture/article/20180306-fact-v-fiction-what-phantom-thread-gets-right-and-wrong\"><u>interview</u></a>, technical consultant and actress Sue Clark (Biddy) details how initially the production team decorated the workroom incorrectly, making it look “pretty” rather than accurate. She emphasizes how the space needed to be more functional (“Fact v Fiction”). She also notes that Reynolds is based on designers Charles Creed, Hardy Amies, and Digby Morton. For more on these couture influences, see Alexander Fury’s “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW240663235 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/28/t-magazine/entertainment/phantom-thread-movie-paul-thomas-anderson.html\"><u>A Film That Pays Homage to the Bygone Era of London Couture</u></a>.”</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:54.45985401459858,250.88321167883208,663.0109489051094,783.0656934306569"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/canvas/1/6dc51eaa-f69f-4d65-ba59-f05a29f612bf","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T14:59:55.614Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Amy de la Haye writes, “London’s couture industry became established after the First World War. Previously, wealthy women had been dressed primarily by London’s court dressmakers, who created etiquette-correct garments — styled along the lines of Paris fashions — for the social life of the British elite, which revolved around the monarchy and the Season. Although the term ‘haute couture’ has never been strictly defined and regulated in Britain (as it is in Paris), London’s couturiers distinguished themselves from the court dressmakers by presenting seasonal collections of directional designs” (de la Haye, “Material Evidence,” 90).&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-00347/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:57.864963503649506,53.025547445255455,259.70802919708046,168.01094890510961"}}}]}]}]}